# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: object-storage
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:object-storage/amazon-s3] Amazon S3 manages data with an object storage architecture which aims to provide scalability, high availability, and low latency with high durability.
[src:object-storage/amazon-s3] The basic storage units of Amazon S3 are objects which are organized into buckets.
[src:object-storage/amazon-s3] Each object is identified by a unique, user-assigned key.
[src:object-storage/amazon-s3] Buckets can be managed using the console provided by Amazon S3, programmatically with the AWS SDK, or the REST application programming interface.
[src:object-storage/amazon-s3] Objects can be up to five terabytes in size.
[src:object-storage/amazon-s3] Requests are authorized using an access control list associated with each object bucket and support versioning which is disabled by default.
[src:object-storage/amazon-s3] Amazon S3 can be used to replace static web-hosting infrastructure with HTTP client-accessible objects, index document support, and error document support.
[src:object-storage/amazon-s3] The Amazon AWS authentication mechanism allows the creation of authenticated URLs, valid for a specified amount of time.
[src:object-storage/amazon-s3] Every item in a bucket can also be served as a BitTorrent feed.
[src:object-storage/amazon-s3] The Amazon S3 store can act as a seed host for a torrent and any BitTorrent client can retrieve the file.
[src:object-storage/amazon-s3] This can drastically reduce the bandwidth cost for the download of popular objects.
[src:object-storage/amazon-s3] A bucket can be configured to save HTTP log information to a sibling bucket; this can be used in data mining operations.
[src:object-storage/amazon-s3] Various User Mode File System (FUSE)–based file systems for Linux or other Unix-like operating systems can be used to mount an S3 bucket as a file system.
[src:object-storage/amazon-s3] The semantics of the Amazon S3 file system are not that of a POSIX file system, so the file system may not behave entirely as expected.
[src:object-storage/amazon-s3] Implementations include Rclone and AWS's own Mountpoint for S3.
[src:object-storage/amazon-s3] Amazon S3 offers nine different storage classes with different levels of durability, availability, and performance requirements.
[src:object-storage/amazon-s3] The Amazon S3 Glacier storage classes above are distinct from Amazon Glacier, which is a separate product with its own APIs.
[src:object-storage/amazon-s3] An object in S3 can be between 0 bytes and 5 TB.
[src:object-storage/amazon-s3] If an object is larger than 5 TB, it must be divided into chunks prior to uploading.
[src:object-storage/amazon-s3] When uploading, Amazon S3 allows a maximum of 5 GB in a single upload operation; hence, objects larger than 5 GB must be uploaded via the S3 multipart upload API.
[src:object-storage/amazon-s3] As of 2025, S3 stores 500 trillion objects, 100s of exabytes of data, serves 200 million requests per second, and peaks at about 1 petabyte per second in bandwidth.
[src:object-storage/amazon-s3] The broad adoption of Amazon S3 and related tooling has given rise to competing services based on the S3 API.
[src:object-storage/amazon-s3] These services use the standard programming interface but are differentiated by their underlying technologies and business models.
[src:object-storage/amazon-s3] A standard interface enables better competition from rival providers and allows economies of scale in implementation, among other benefits.
[src:object-storage/amazon-s3] Users are not required to go directly to Amazon as several storage providers such as Cloudian, Backblaze B2, Wasabi offer S3-compatible storage with options of on-premises and private cloud deployments.
[src:object-storage/amazon-s3] Several open-source implementations of S3-compatible object store servers can be self-hosted, such as Garage.
[src:object-storage/amazon-s3] IBM Cloud Object Storage also offers a cloud-based S3-compatible option of Object Storage.
[src:object-storage/amazon-s3] Amazon Web Services introduced Amazon S3 in 2006.
[src:object-storage/amazon-s3] In November 2017, AWS added default encryption capabilities at bucket level.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] Cloud storage services may be accessed through a colocated cloud computing service, a web service application programming interface (API) or by applications that use the API, such as cloud desktop storage, a cloud storage gateway or Web-based content management systems.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] Cloud computing is believed to have been invented by J.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] Licklider in the 1960s with his work on ARPANET to connect people and data from anywhere at any time.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] In 1983, CompuServe offered its consumer users a small amount of disk space that could be used to store any files they chose to upload.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] In 1994, AT&T launched PersonaLink Services, an online platform for personal and business communication and entrepreneurship.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] In 2005, Box announced an online file sharing and personal cloud content management service for businesses.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] Alibaba Cloud was launched in September 2009, three years after AWS.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] As of 2024, Gartner ranked cloud storage platforms as follows: AWS, Google, Microsoft, Oracle, Alibaba, IBM, Huawei and Tencent.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] These account for 97% of the global cloud services market.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] This rating was based on ability to execute in market and innovation vision.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] In 2023, 80% of China's technology companies and half of AI LLM companies ran on Alibaba Cloud while in the US dominance belonged to AWS with 31 to 50% share.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] In 2026, Alibaba is scheduled to spend more than 300 million yuan, about $52 billion, on artificial intelligence and cloud infrastructure over the next three years, a figure much larger than the amount spent the previous year.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] Data centers will also be expanding, and AI models like Qwen.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] Alibaba's CEO, Eddie Wu, describes the amount spent as the largest to date on cloud and AI.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] Also, he explained that they expect much of the internal AI workload to run on Alibaba Cloud.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] Spending will include specific items such as GPU-like accelerators and large-scale data centers to support internal workloads and external client functions, underscoring Alibaba's pivot from e-commerce to cloud infrastructure.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] Cloud storage is based on highly virtualized infrastructure and is like broader cloud computing in terms of interfaces, near-instant elasticity and scalability, multi-tenancy, and metered resources.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] Cloud storage services can be used from an off-premises service (Amazon S3) or deployed on-premises (ViON Capacity Services).
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] There are three types of cloud storage: a hosted object storage service, file storage, and block storage.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] Each of these cloud storage types offer their own unique advantages.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] Security of stored data and data in transit may be a concern when storing sensitive data at a cloud storage provider.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] Outsourcing data storage increases the attack surface area.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] Cloud storage is a rich resource for both hackers and national security agencies.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] Because the cloud holds data from many different users and organizations, hackers see it as a very valuable target.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] The number of people with access to the data who could be compromised (e.g., bribed, or coerced) increases dramatically.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] Decryption keys that are kept by the service user, as opposed to the service provider, limit access to data by service provider employees.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] As for sharing multiple data in the cloud with multiple users, a large number of keys has to be distributed to users via secure channels for decryption, also it has to be securely stored and managed by the users in their devices.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] Storing these keys requires rather expensive secure storage.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] To overcome that, key-aggregate cryptosystem can be used.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] It increases the number of networks over which the data travels.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] Instead of just a local area network (LAN) or storage area network (SAN), data stored on a cloud requires a WAN (wide area network) to connect them both.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] By sharing storage and networks with many other users/customers it is possible for other customers to access your data.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] Sometimes because of erroneous actions, faulty equipment, a bug and sometimes because of criminal intent.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] This risk applies to all types of storage and not only cloud storage.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] The risk of having data read during transmission can be mitigated through encryption technology.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] Encryption in transit protects data as it is being transmitted to and from the cloud service.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] Encryption at rest protects data that is stored at the service provider.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] Encrypting data in an on-premises cloud service on-ramp system can provide both kinds of encryption protection.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] There are several options available to avoid security issues.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] One option is to use a private cloud instead of a public cloud.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] Another option is to ingest data in an encrypted format where the key is held within the on-premise infrastructure.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] To this end, access is often by use of on-premise cloud storage gateways that have options to encrypt the data prior to transfer.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] Typically, cloud storage Service Level Agreements (SLAs) do not encompass all forms of service interruptions.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] Exclusions typically include planned maintenance, downtime resulting from external factors such as network issues, human errors like misconfigurations, natural disasters, force majeure events, or security breaches.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] Typically, customers bear the responsibility of monitoring SLA compliance and must file claims for any unmet SLAs within a designated timeframe.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] Customers should be aware of how deviations from SLAs are calculated, as these parameters may vary by other services offered within the same provider.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] These requirements can place a considerable burden on customers.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] Additionally, SLA percentages and conditions can differ across various services within the same provider, with some services lacking any SLA altogether.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] In cases of service interruptions due to hardware failures in the cloud provider, service providers typically do not offer monetary compensation.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] Instead, eligible users may receive credits as outlined in the corresponding SLA.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] Hybrid cloud storage is a term for a storage infrastructure that uses a combination of on-premises storage resources with cloud storage.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] The on-premises storage is usually managed by the organization, while the public cloud storage provider is responsible for the management and security of the data stored in the cloud.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] Hybrid cloud storage can be implemented by an on-premises cloud storage gateway that presents a file system or object storage interface that users can access in the same way they would access a local storage system.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] The cloud storage gateway transparently transfers the data to and from the cloud storage service, providing low latency access to the data through a local cache.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] Hybrid cloud storage can be used to supplement an organization's internal storage resources, or it can be used as the primary storage infrastructure.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] In either case, hybrid cloud storage can provide organizations with greater flexibility and scalability than traditional on-premises storage infrastructure.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] There are several benefits to using hybrid cloud storage, including the ability to cache frequently used data on-site for quick access, while inactive cold data is stored off-site in the cloud.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] This can save space, reduce storage costs and improve performance.
[src:object-storage/cloud-storage] Additionally, hybrid cloud storage can provide organizations with greater redundancy and fault tolerance, as data is stored in both on-premises and cloud storage infrastructure.
[src:object-storage/data-lake] A **data lake** is a system or repository of data stored in its natural, raw format, usually object blobs or files.
[src:object-storage/data-lake] A data lake is usually a single store of data including raw copies of source system data, sensor data, social data etc., and transformed data used for tasks such as reporting, visualization, advanced analytics, and machine learning.
[src:object-storage/data-lake] A data lake can include structured data from relational databases (rows and columns), semi-structured data (CSV, logs, XML, JSON), unstructured data (emails, documents, PDFs), and binary data (images, audio, video).
[src:object-storage/data-lake] A data lake can be established *on premises* (within an organization's data centers) or *in the cloud* (using cloud services).
[src:object-storage/data-lake] James Dixon, then chief technology officer at Pentaho, coined the term by 2011 to contrast it with data mart, which is a smaller repository of interesting attributes derived from raw data.
[src:object-storage/data-lake] In promoting data lakes, he argued that data marts have several inherent problems, such as information siloing.
[src:object-storage/data-lake] PricewaterhouseCoopers (PwC) said that data lakes could "put an end to data silos".
[src:object-storage/data-lake] Many companies use cloud storage services such as Google Cloud Storage and Amazon S3 or a distributed file system such as Apache Hadoop distributed file system (HDFS).
[src:object-storage/data-lake] There is a gradual academic interest in the concept of data lakes.
[src:object-storage/data-lake] For example, Personal DataLake at Cardiff University is a new type of data lake which aims at managing big data of individual users by providing a single point of collecting, organizing, and sharing personal data.
[src:object-storage/data-lake] Early data lakes, such as Hadoop 1.0, had limited capabilities because it only supported batch-oriented processing (Map Reduce).
[src:object-storage/data-lake] Interacting with it required expertise in Java, map reduce and higher-level tools like Apache Pig, Apache Spark and Apache Hive (which were also originally batch-oriented).
[src:object-storage/data-lake] Poorly managed data lakes have been facetiously called data swamps.
[src:object-storage/data-lake] In June 2015, David Needle characterized "so-called data lakes" as "one of the more controversial ways to manage big data".
[src:object-storage/data-lake] PwC was also careful to note in their research that not all data lake initiatives are successful.
[src:object-storage/data-lake] They describe companies that build successful data lakes as gradually maturing their lake as they figure out which data and metadata are important to the organization.
[src:object-storage/data-lake] Another criticism is that the term *data lake* is used with many different meanings.
[src:object-storage/data-lake] It may be used to refer to, for example: any tools or data management practices that are not data warehouses; a particular technology for implementation; a raw data reservoir; a hub for ETL offload; or a central hub for self-service analytics.
[src:object-storage/data-lake] While critiques of data lakes are warranted, in many cases they apply to other data projects as well.
[src:object-storage/data-lake] For example, the definition of *data warehouse* is also changeable, and not all data warehouse efforts have been successful.
[src:object-storage/data-lake] In response to various critiques, McKinsey noted that the data lake should be viewed as a service model for delivering business value within the enterprise, not a technology outcome.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] The fraction *r* = *k*/*n* is called the code rate.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] The fraction *k’/k*, where *k’* denotes the number of symbols required for recovery, is called reception efficiency.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] The recovery algorithm expects that it is known which of the *n* symbols are lost.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] Erasure coding was invented by Irving Reed and Gustave Solomon in 1960.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] There are many different erasure coding schemes.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] The most popular erasure codes are Reed-Solomon coding, low-density parity-check code (LDPC codes), and turbo codes.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] While technically RAID can be seen as a kind of erasure code, RAID is generally applied to an array attached to a single host computer (which is a single point of failure), while "erasure coding" generally implies multiple hosts, sometimes called a redundant array of inexpensive servers (RAIS).
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] The erasure code allows operations to continue when any one of those hosts stops.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] Compared to block-level RAID systems, object storage erasure coding has some significant differences that make it more resilient.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] Optimal erasure codes have the property that any *k* out of the *n* code word symbols are sufficient to recover the original message (i.e., they have optimal reception efficiency).
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] Optimal erasure codes are maximum distance separable codes (MDS codes).
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] Parity check is the special case where *n*= *k* + 1.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] The set of *k* + 1 values $\{v_{i}\}_{1\leq i\leq k+1}$ is now consistent with regard to the checksum.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] RAID 5 is a widely used application of the parity check erasure code using XOR.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] In the simple case where *k* = 2, redundancy symbols may be created by sampling different points along the line between the two original symbols.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] Alice wants to send her telephone number (555629) to Bob using err-mail.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] Messages longer than 5 characters are illegal.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] It is very expensive (similar to air-mail).
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] Instead of asking Bob to acknowledge the messages she sends, Alice devises the following scheme.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] Bob knows that the form of *f*(*k*) is $f(i)=a+(b-a)(i-1)$ , where *a* and *b* are the two parts of the telephone number.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] Bob can reconstruct Alice's phone number by computing the values of *a* and *b* from the values (*f*(4) and *f*(5)) he has received.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] Bob can perform this procedure using any two err-mails, so the erasure code in this example has a rate of 40%.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] Note that Alice cannot encode her telephone number in just one err-mail, because it contains six characters, and that the maximum length of one err-mail message is five characters.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] If she sent her phone number in pieces, asking Bob to acknowledge receipt of each piece, at least four messages would have to be sent anyway (two from Alice, and two acknowledgments from Bob).
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] So the erasure code in this example, which requires five messages, is quite economical.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] For truly generic erasure codes that work over any data set, we would need something other than the *f*(*i*) given.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] The linear construction above can be generalized to polynomial interpolation.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] Additionally, points are now computed over a finite field.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] First we choose a finite field *F* with order of at least *n*, but usually a power of 2.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] The sender numbers the data symbols from 0 to *k* − 1 and sends them.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] He then constructs a (Lagrange) polynomial *p*(*x*) of order *k* such that *p*(*i*) is equal to data symbol *i*.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] The receiver can now also use polynomial interpolation to recover the lost packets, provided he receives *k* symbols successfully.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] If the order of *F* is less than 2*b*, where b is the number of bits in a symbol, then multiple polynomials can be used.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] The sender can construct symbols *k* to *n* − 1 'on the fly', i.e., distribute the workload evenly between transmission of the symbols.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] If the receiver wants to do his calculations 'on the fly', he can construct a new polynomial *q*, such that *q*(*i*) = *p*(*i*) if symbol *i* < *k* was received successfully and *q*(*i*) = 0 when symbol *i* < *k* was not received.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] Firstly we know that *r*(*i*) = 0 if symbol *i* < *k* has been received successfully.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] Secondly, if symbol *i* ≥ *k* has been received successfully, then *r*(*i*) = *p*(*i*) − *q*(*i*) can be calculated.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] So we have enough data points to construct *r* and evaluate it to find the lost packets.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] So both the sender and the receiver require *O*(*n* (*n* − *k*)) operations and only *O*(*n* − *k*) space for operating 'on the fly'.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] This process is implemented by Reed–Solomon codes, with code words constructed over a finite field using a Vandermonde matrix.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] Most practical erasure codes are systematic codes—each one of the original *k* symbols can be found copied, unencoded, as one of the *n* message symbols.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] (Erasure codes that support secret sharing never use a systematic code).
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] Fountain codes (also known as *rateless erasure codes*) are notable examples of *near-optimal erasure codes*.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] They can transform a *k* symbol message into a practically infinite encoded form, i.e., they can generate an arbitrary amount of redundancy symbols that can all be used for error correction.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] Receivers can start decoding after they have received slightly more than *k* encoded symbols.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] Regenerating codes address the issue of rebuilding (also called repairing) lost encoded fragments from existing encoded fragments.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] This issue occurs in distributed storage systems where communication to maintain encoded redundancy is a problem.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] Erasure coding is now standard practice for reliable data storage.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] In particular, various implementations of Reed-Solomon erasure coding are used by Apache Hadoop, the RAID-6 built into Linux, Microsoft Azure, Facebook cold storage, and Backblaze Vaults.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] The classical way to recover from failures in storage systems was to use replication.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] However, replication incurs significant overhead in terms of wasted bytes.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] Therefore, increasingly large storage systems, such as those used in data centers use erasure-coded storage.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] The most common form of erasure coding used in storage systems is Reed-Solomon (RS) code, an advanced mathematics formula used to enable regeneration of missing data from pieces of known data, called parity blocks.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] In a (*k*, *r*) RS code, a given set of *k* data blocks, called "chunks", are encoded into (*k* + *r*) chunks.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] The total set of chunks comprises a *stripe*.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] The coding is done such that as long as at least *k* out of (*k* + *r*) chunks are available, one can recover the entire data.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] This means a (*k*, *r*) RS-encoded storage can tolerate up to *r* failures.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] In the case of a fully replicated system, the 10 MB of user data will have to be replicated 4 times to tolerate up to 4 concurrent failures.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] The storage overhead in that case will be 50/10 = 5.0×.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] This gives an idea of the lower storage overhead of erasure-coded storage compared to full replication and thus the attraction in today's storage systems.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] The *Hitchhiker* scheme can be combined with RS-coding to reduce the amount of computation and data-transfer required for data block reconstruction.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] It is also implemented as an HDFS codec, though a policy will need to be manually defined for it to be used.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] Initially, erasure codes were used to reduce the cost of storing "cold" (rarely-accessed) data efficiently; but erasure codes can also be used to improve performance serving "hot" (more-frequently-accessed) data compared to simpler redundancy schemes (mirroring).
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] The classic example of erasing coding improving performance is RAID 5, which provides the same single-drive failure protection while requiring fewer hard drives compared to RAID 1.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] The extra hard drives may then be used to store more data and make use of the improved read/write-speed multiplier on RAID 5.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] This also applies to RAID 6 (double-redundancy: one parity and one erasure code), assuming processing power is sufficient.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] Generalized RAID can work with any number of redundancy drives.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] There are two notations for generalized RAID: RAID7.*x* refers to a system with *x* redundancy drives, allowing recovery when as many as *x* drives fail.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] Alternatively, RAID N+M refers to N regular data drives with M redundancy drives, being able to recover all the data when any M drives fail.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] A more advanced example is *EC-Cache*, a cluster cache, i.e. a cache distributed among several nodes.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] Such systems can suffer from load imbalance when one node happens to host more popular items and a common method to address this issue is *selective replication*, i.e. create more replicas for more popular objects.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] However, this method is limited by the available amount of memory.
[src:object-storage/erasure-code] By individually dividing *every* object into *k* splits and *r* redundancy units, perfect load balancing can instead be achieved with minimal waste of memory.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Object storage systems allow retention of massive amounts of unstructured data in which data is written once and read once (or many times).
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Object storage is used for purposes such as storing objects like videos and photos on Facebook, songs on Spotify, or files in online collaboration services, such as Dropbox.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] One of the limitations with object storage is that it is not intended for transactional data, as object storage was not designed to replace NAS file access and sharing; it does not support the locking and sharing mechanisms needed to maintain a single, accurately updated version of a file.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Jim Starkey coined the term ***blob*** working at Digital Equipment Corporation to refer to opaque data entities.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] The terminology was adopted for Rdb/VMS.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] *Blob* is often humorously explained to be an abbreviation for *binary large object*.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] According to Starkey, this backronym arose when Terry McKiever, working in marketing at Apollo Computer felt that the term needed to be an abbreviation.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] McKiever began using the expansion *basic large object*.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] This was later eclipsed by the retroactive explanation of blobs as *binary large objects*.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] According to Starkey, "Blob don't stand for nothin'." Rejecting the acronym, he explained his motivation behind the coinage, saying, "A blob is the thing that ate Cincinnatti [*sic*], Cleveland, or whatever", referring to the 1958 science fiction film *The Blob*.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] In 1995, research led by Garth Gibson on Network-Attached Secure Disks first promoted the concept of splitting less common operations, like namespace manipulations, from common operations, like reads and writes, to optimize the performance and scale of both.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] In the same year, a Belgian company – FilePool – was established to build the basis for archiving functions.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Object storage was proposed at Gibson's Carnegie Mellon University lab as a research project in 1996.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Another key concept was abstracting the writes and reads of data to more flexible data containers (objects).
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Fine grained access control through object storage architecture was further described by one of the NASD team, Howard Gobioff, who later was one of the inventors of the Google File System.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Other related work includes the Coda filesystem project at Carnegie Mellon, which started in 1987, and spawned the Lustre file system.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] There is also the OceanStore project at UC Berkeley, which started in 1999 and the Logistical Networking project at the University of Tennessee Knoxville, which started in 1998.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] In 1999, Gibson founded Panasas to commercialize the concepts developed by the NASD team.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Seagate Technology played a central role in the development of object storage.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] This paper was proposed to INCITS T-10 (International Committee for Information Technology Standards) with a goal to form a committee and design a specification based on the SCSI interface protocol.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] This defined objects as abstracted data, with unique identifiers and metadata, how objects related to file systems, along with many other innovative concepts.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Anderson presented many of these ideas at the SNIA conference in October 1999.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] The presentation revealed an IP Agreement that had been signed in February 1997 between the original collaborators (with Seagate represented by Anderson and Chris Malakapalli) and covered the benefits of object storage, scalable computing, platform independence, and storage management.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] One of the design principles of object storage is to abstract some of the lower layers of storage away from the administrators and applications.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Thus, data is exposed and managed as objects instead of blocks or (exclusively) files.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Objects contain additional descriptive properties which can be used for better indexing or management.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Administrators do not have to perform lower-level storage functions like constructing and managing logical volumes to utilize disk capacity or setting RAID levels to deal with disk failure.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Object storage also allows the addressing and identification of individual objects by more than just file name and file path.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Object storage adds a unique identifier within a bucket, or across the entire system, to support much larger namespaces and eliminate name collisions.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Object storage explicitly separates file metadata from data to support additional capabilities.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Object storage provides programmatic interfaces to allow applications to manipulate data.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] At the base level, this includes Create, read, update and delete (CRUD) functions for basic read, write and delete operations.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Some object storage implementations go further, supporting additional functionality like object/file versioning, object replication, life-cycle management and movement of objects between different tiers and types of storage.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Most API implementations are REST-based, allowing the use of many standard HTTP calls.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] The vast majority of cloud storage available in the market leverages an object-storage architecture.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Some notable examples are Amazon S3, which debuted in March 2006, Microsoft Azure Blob Storage, IBM Cloud Object Storage, Rackspace Cloud Files (whose code was donated in 2010 to Openstack project and released as OpenStack Swift), and Google Cloud Storage released in May 2010.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Some distributed file systems use an object-based architecture, where file metadata is stored in metadata servers and file data is stored in object storage servers.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] File system client software interacts with the distinct servers, and abstracts them to present a full file system to users and applications.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Some early incarnations of object storage were used for archiving, as implementations were optimized for data services like immutability, not performance.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] EMC Centera and Hitachi HCP (formerly known as HCAP) are two commonly cited object storage products for archiving.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Another example is Quantum ActiveScale Object Storage Platform.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] More general-purpose object-storage systems came to market around 2008.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] A few object-storage systems support Unified File and Object storage, allowing clients to store objects on a storage system while simultaneously other clients store files on the same storage system.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Other vendors in the area of Hybrid cloud storage are using Cloud storage gateways to provide a file access layer over object storage, implementing file access protocols such as SMB and NFS.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Some large Internet companies developed their own software when object-storage products were not commercially available or use cases were very specific.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Facebook famously invented their own object-storage software, code-named Haystack, to address their particular massive-scale photo management needs efficiently.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Object storage at the protocol and device layer was proposed 20 years ago and approved for the SCSI command set nearly 10 years ago as "Object-based Storage Device Commands" (OSD), however, it had not been put into production until the development of the Seagate Kinetic Open Storage platform.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] The SCSI command set for Object Storage Devices was developed by a working group of the SNIA for the T10 committee of the International Committee for Information Technology Standards (INCITS).
[src:object-storage/object-storage] T10 is responsible for all SCSI standards.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] One of the first object-storage products, Lustre, is used in 70% of the Top 100 supercomputers and ~50% of the Top 500.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] As of June 16, 2013, this includes 7 of the top 10, including the current fourth fastest system on the list - China's Tianhe-2 and the seventh fastest, the Titan supercomputer at the Oak Ridge National Laboratory.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Object-storage systems had good adoption in the early 2000s as an archive platform, particularly in the wake of compliance laws like Sarbanes-Oxley.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] After five years in the market, EMC's Centera product claimed over 3,500 customers and 150 petabytes shipped by 2007.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Hitachi's HCP product also claims many petabyte-scale customers.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Newer object storage systems have also gotten some traction, particularly around very large custom applications like eBay's auction site, where EMC Atmos is used to manage over 500 million objects a day.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] As of March 3, 2014, EMC claims to have sold over 1.5 exabytes of Atmos storage.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] On July 1, 2014, Los Alamos National Lab chose the Scality RING as the basis for a 500-petabyte storage environment, which would be among the largest ever.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] "Captive" object storage systems like Facebook's Haystack have scaled impressively.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] In April 2009, Haystack was managing 60 billion photos and 1.5 petabytes of storage, adding 220 million photos and 25 terabytes a week.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Facebook more recently stated that they were adding 350 million photos a day and were storing 240 billion photos.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] This could equal as much as 357 petabytes.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Cloud storage has become pervasive as many new web and mobile applications choose it as a common way to store binary data.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] As the storage back-end to many popular applications like Smugmug and Dropbox, Amazon S3 has grown to massive scale, citing over 2-trillion objects stored in April 2013.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Two months later, Microsoft claimed that they stored even more objects in Azure at 8.5 trillion.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] By April 2014, Azure claimed over 20-trillion objects stored.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Windows Azure Storage manages Blobs (user files), Tables (structured storage), and Queues (message delivery) and counts them all as objects.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Coldago Research adopted qualitative and quantitative analysis of the object storage market to rank 13 notable vendors based on technological capabilities, market momentum, and innovation trajectory.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] The 2024 Coldago object storage market leader rating is in alphabetical order: Cloudian, DataCore, Dell EMC, Huawei, IBM, MinIO, Pure Storage, Quantum, and VAST Data.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] In the first version of the OSD standard, objects are specified with a 64-bit partition ID and a 64-bit object ID.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Partitions are created and deleted within an OSD, and objects are created and deleted within partitions.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] There are no fixed sizes associated with partitions or objects; they are allowed to grow subject to physical size limitations of the device or logical quota constraints on a partition.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] An extensible set of attributes describe objects.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Some attributes are implemented directly by the OSD, such as the number of bytes in an object and the modification time of an object.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] There is a special policy tag attribute that is part of the security mechanism.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Other attributes are uninterpreted by the OSD.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] These are set on objects by the higher-level storage systems that use the OSD for persistent storage.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] For example, attributes might be used to classify objects, or to capture relationships among different objects stored on different OSDs.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] A list command returns a list of identifiers for objects within a partition, optionally filtered by matches against their attribute values.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] A list command can also return selected attributes of the listed objects.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Read and write commands can be combined, or piggy-backed, with commands to get and set attributes.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] This ability reduces the number of times a high-level storage system has to cross the interface to the OSD, which can improve overall efficiency.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] A second generation of the SCSI command set, "Object-Based Storage Devices - 2" (OSD-2) added support for snapshots, collections of objects, and improved error handling.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] A snapshot is a point-in-time copy of all the objects in a partition into a new partition.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] The OSD can implement a space-efficient copy using copy-on-write techniques so that the two partitions share objects that are unchanged between the snapshots, or the OSD might physically copy the data to the new partition.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] The standard defines clones, which are writeable, and snapshots, which are read-only.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] A collection is a special kind of object that contains the identifiers of other objects.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] There are operations to add and delete from collections, and there are operations to get or set attributes for all the objects in a collection.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Collections are also used for error reporting.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] If an object becomes damaged by the occurrence of a media defect (i.e., a bad spot on the disk) or by a software error within the OSD implementation, its identifier is put into a special error collection.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] The higher-level storage system that uses the OSD can query this collection and take corrective action as necessary.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] The border between an object store and a key–value store is blurred, with key–value stores being sometimes loosely referred to as object stores.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] A traditional block storage interface uses a series of fixed size blocks which are numbered starting at 0.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Data must be that exact fixed size and can be stored in a particular block which is identified by its logical block number (LBN).
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Later, one can retrieve that block of data by specifying its unique LBN.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] With a key–value store, data is identified by a key rather than a LBN.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] A key might be "cat" or "olive" or "42".
[src:object-storage/object-storage] It can be an arbitrary sequence of bytes of arbitrary length.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Data (called a value in this parlance) does not need to be a fixed size and also can be an arbitrary sequence of bytes of arbitrary length.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] One stores data by presenting the key and data (value) to the data store and can later retrieve the data by presenting the key.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] This concept is seen in programming languages.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Python calls them dictionaries, Perl calls them hashes, Java, Rust and C++ call them maps, etc.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Several data stores also implement key–value stores such as Memcached, Redis and CouchDB.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Object stores are similar to key–value stores in two respects.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] First, the object identifier or URL (the equivalent of the key) can be an arbitrary string.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Second, data may be of an arbitrary size.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] There are, however, a few key differences between key–value stores and object stores.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] First, object stores also allow one to associate a limited set of attributes (metadata) with each piece of data.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] The combination of a key, value, and set of attributes is referred to as an object.
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Second, object stores are optimized for large amounts of data (hundreds of megabytes or even gigabytes), whereas for key–value stores the value is expected to be relatively small (kilobytes).
[src:object-storage/object-storage] Finally, object stores usually offer weaker consistency guarantees such as eventual consistency, whereas key–value stores offer strong consistency.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] A **storage area network** (**SAN**) or **storage network** is a computer network which provides access to consolidated, block-level data storage.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] SANs are primarily used to access data storage devices, such as disk arrays and tape libraries from servers so that the devices appear to the operating system as direct-attached storage.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] A SAN typically is a dedicated network of storage devices not accessible through the local area network (LAN).
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] Although a SAN provides only block-level access, file systems built on top of SANs do provide file-level access and are known as shared-disk file systems.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] Newer SAN configurations enable hybrid SAN and allow traditional block storage that appears as local storage but also object storage for web services through APIs.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] Storage area networks (SANs) are sometimes referred to as *network behind the servers* and historically developed out of a centralized data storage model, but with its own data network.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] A SAN is, at its simplest, a dedicated network for data storage.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] In addition to storing data, SANs allow for the automatic backup of data, and the monitoring of the storage as well as the backup process.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] A SAN is a combination of hardware and software.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] It grew out of data-centric mainframe architectures, where clients in a network can connect to several servers that store different types of data.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] To scale storage capacities as the volumes of data grew, direct-attached storage (DAS) was developed, where disk arrays or just a bunch of disks (JBODs) were attached to servers.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] In this architecture, storage devices can be added to increase storage capacity.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] However, the server through which the storage devices are accessed is a single point of failure, and a large part of the LAN network bandwidth is used for accessing, storing and backing up data.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] To solve the single point of failure issue, a *direct-attached shared storage* architecture was implemented, where several servers could access the same storage device.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] DAS was the first network storage system and is still widely used where data storage requirements are not very high.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] Out of it developed the network-attached storage (NAS) architecture, where one or more dedicated file server or storage devices are made available in a LAN.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] Therefore, the transfer of data, particularly for backup, still takes place over the existing LAN.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] If more than a terabyte of data was stored at any one time, LAN bandwidth became a bottleneck.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] Therefore, SANs were developed, where a dedicated storage network was attached to the LAN, and terabytes of data are transferred over a dedicated high speed and bandwidth network.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] Within the SAN, storage devices are interconnected.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] Transfer of data between storage devices, such as for backup, happens behind the servers and is meant to be transparent.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] In a NAS architecture data is transferred using the TCP and IP protocols over Ethernet.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] Distinct protocols were developed for SANs, such as Fibre Channel, iSCSI, Infiniband.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] Therefore, SANs often have their own network and storage devices, which have to be bought, installed, and configured.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] This makes SANs inherently more expensive than NAS architectures.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] SANs have their own networking devices, such as SAN switches.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] To access the SAN, so-called SAN servers are used, which in turn connect to SAN host adapters.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] Within the SAN, a range of data storage devices may be interconnected, such as SAN-capable disk arrays, JBODs and tape libraries.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] Servers that allow access to the SAN and its storage devices are said to form the *host layer* of the SAN.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] Such servers have host adapters, which are cards that attach to slots on the server motherboard (usually PCI slots) and run with a corresponding firmware and device driver.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] Through the host adapters the operating system of the server can communicate with the storage devices in the SAN.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] In Fibre channel deployments, a cable connects to the host adapter through the gigabit interface converter (GBIC).
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] GBICs are also used on switches and storage devices within the SAN, and they convert digital bits into light impulses that can then be transmitted over the Fibre Channel cables.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] Conversely, the GBIC converts incoming light impulses back into digital bits.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] The predecessor of the GBIC was called gigabit link module (GLM).
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] The fabric layer consists of SAN networking devices that include SAN switches, routers, protocol bridges, gateway devices, and cables.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] SAN network devices move data within the SAN, or between an *initiator*, such as an HBA port of a server, and a *target*, such as the port of a storage device.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] When SANs were first built, hubs were the only devices that were Fibre Channel capable, but Fibre Channel switches were developed and hubs are now rarely found in SANs.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] Switches have the advantage over hubs that they allow all attached devices to communicate simultaneously, as a switch provides a dedicated link to connect all its ports with one another.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] When SANs were first built, Fibre Channel had to be implemented over copper cables, these days multimode optical fibre cables are used in SANs.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] SANs are usually built with redundancy, so SAN switches are connected with redundant links.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] SAN switches connect the servers with the storage devices and are typically non-blocking allowing transmission of data across all attached wires at the same time.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] SAN switches are for redundancy purposes set up in a meshed topology.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] A single SAN switch can have as few as 8 ports and up to 32 ports with modular extensions.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] So-called director-class switches can have as many as 128 ports.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] In switched SANs, the Fibre Channel switched fabric protocol FC-SW-6 is used under which every device in the SAN has a hardcoded World Wide Name (WWN) address in the host bus adapter (HBA).
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] If a device is connected to the SAN its WWN is registered in the SAN switch name server.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] In place of a WWN, or worldwide port name (WWPN), SAN Fibre Channel storage device vendors may also hardcode a worldwide node name (WWNN).
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] The ports of storage devices often have a WWN starting with 5, while the bus adapters of servers start with 10 or 21.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] The serialized Small Computer Systems Interface (SCSI) protocol is often used on top of the Fibre Channel switched fabric protocol in servers and SAN storage devices.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] The Internet Small Computer Systems Interface (iSCSI) over Ethernet and the Infiniband protocols may also be found implemented in SANs, but are often bridged into the Fibre Channel SAN.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] However, Infiniband and iSCSI storage devices, in particular, disk arrays, are available.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] The various storage devices in a SAN are said to form the *storage layer*.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] It can include a variety of hard disk and magnetic tape devices that store data.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] In SANs, disk arrays are joined through a RAID which makes a lot of hard disks look and perform like one big storage device.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] Every storage device, or even partition on that storage device, has a logical unit number (LUN) assigned to it.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] Every node in the SAN, be it a server or another storage device, can access the storage by referencing the LUN.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] The LUNs allow for the storage capacity of a SAN to be segmented and for the implementation of access controls.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] A particular server, or a group of servers, may, for example, be only given access to a particular part of the SAN storage layer, in the form of LUNs.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] When a storage device receives a request to read or write data, it will check its access list to establish whether the node, identified by its LUN, is allowed to access the storage area, also identified by a LUN.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] LUN masking is a technique whereby the host bus adapter and the SAN software of a server restrict the LUNs for which commands are accepted.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] In doing so LUNs that should never be accessed by the server are masked.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] Another method to restrict server access to particular SAN storage devices is fabric-based access control, or zoning, which is enforced by the SAN networking devices and servers.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] Under zoning, server access is restricted to storage devices that are in a particular SAN zone.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] Storage networks may also be built using Serial Attached SCSI (SAS) and Serial ATA (SATA) technologies.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] SAS evolved from SCSI direct-attached storage.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] SATA evolved from Parallel ATA direct-attached storage.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] SAS and SATA devices can be networked using SAS expanders.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] The Storage Networking Industry Association (SNIA) defines a SAN as "a network whose primary purpose is the transfer of data between computer systems and storage elements".
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] But a SAN does not just consist of a communication infrastructure, it also has a software *management layer*.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] This software organizes the servers, storage devices, and the network so that data can be transferred and stored.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] Because a SAN does not use direct attached storage (DAS), the storage devices in the SAN are not owned and managed by a server.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] A SAN allows a server to access a large data storage capacity and this storage capacity may also be accessible by other servers.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] Moreover, SAN software must ensure that data is directly moved between storage devices within the SAN, with minimal server intervention.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] SAN management software is installed on one or more servers and management clients on the storage devices.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] Two approaches have developed in SAN management software: in-band and out-of-band management.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] In-band means that management data between server and storage devices is transmitted on the same network as the storage data.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] While out-of-band means that management data is transmitted over dedicated links.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] SAN management software will collect management data from all storage devices in the storage layer.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] This includes info on read and write failures, storage capacity bottlenecks and failure of storage devices.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] SAN management software may integrate with the Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP).
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] In 1999 Common Information Model (CIM), an open standard, was introduced for managing storage devices and to provide interoperability, The web-based version of CIM is called Web-Based Enterprise Management (WBEM) and defines SAN storage device objects and process transactions.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] Use of these protocols involves a CIM object manager (CIMOM), to manage objects and interactions, and allows for the central management of SAN storage devices.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] Basic device management for SANs can also be achieved through the Storage Management Interface Specification (SMI-S), were CIM objects and processes are registered in a directory.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] Software applications and subsystems can then draw on this directory.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] Management software applications are also available to configure SAN storage devices, allowing, for example, the configuration of zones and LUNs.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] Ultimately SAN networking and storage devices are available from many vendors and every SAN vendor has its own management and configuration software.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] Common management in SANs that include devices from different vendors is only possible if vendors make the application programming interface (API) for their devices available to other vendors.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] In such cases, upper-level SAN management software can manage the SAN devices from other vendors.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] In a SAN, data is transferred, stored and accessed on a block level.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] As such, a SAN does not provide data file abstraction, only block-level storage and operations.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] Server operating systems maintain their own file systems on their own dedicated, non-shared LUNs on the SAN, as though they were local to themselves.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] If multiple systems were simply to attempt to share a LUN, these would interfere with each other and quickly corrupt the data.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] Any planned sharing of data on different computers within a LUN requires software.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] File systems have been developed to work with SAN software to provide file-level access.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] These are known as shared-disk file system.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] Video editing systems require very high data transfer rates and very low latency.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] SANs in media and entertainment are often referred to as serverless due to the nature of the configuration which places the video workflow (ingest, editing, playout) desktop clients directly on the SAN rather than attaching to servers.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] Control of data flow is managed by a distributed file system.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] Per-node bandwidth usage control, sometimes referred to as quality of service (QoS), is especially important in video editing as it ensures fair and prioritized bandwidth usage across the network.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] SAN Storage QoS enables the desired storage performance to be calculated and maintained for network customers accessing the device.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] Alternatively, over-provisioning can be used to provide additional capacity to compensate for peak network traffic loads.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] However, where network loads are not predictable, over-provisioning can eventually cause all bandwidth to be fully consumed and latency to increase significantly resulting in SAN performance degradation.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] Storage virtualization is the process of abstracting logical storage from physical storage.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] The physical storage resources are aggregated into storage pools, from which the logical storage is created.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] It presents to the user a logical space for data storage and transparently handles the process of mapping it to the physical location, a concept called location transparency.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] This is implemented in modern disk arrays, often using vendor-proprietary technology.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] However, the goal of storage virtualization is to group multiple disk arrays from different vendors, scattered over a network, into a single storage device.
[src:object-storage/storage-area-network] The single storage device can then be managed uniformly.
